<problem display_name="Row of All Zeros" linenum="232" tex_filename="./block1/linearequations.tex" showanswer="finished" attempts="2" rerandomize="per_student">
  <text>
    <p>
Suppose you have an augmented matrix and, after a few elementary row operations, you see one row that looks like this: </p>
    <p>
[mathjaxinline]\left[ \begin{array}{cccc:c} 0 &amp;  0 &amp;  0 &amp;  0 &amp;  0 \end{array} \right][/mathjaxinline] </p>
    <p>
Just from the presence of that one row, what can you conclude about the overall system? </p>
    <p>
      <multiplechoiceresponse>
        <choicegroup direction="vertical">
          <choice correct="false" name="1">
            <text> The system is consistent and has a unique solution</text>
          </choice>
          <choice correct="false" name="2">
            <text> The system is consistent but has more than one solution</text>
          </choice>
          <choice correct="false" name="3">
            <text> The system is inconsistent</text>
          </choice>
          <choice correct="true" name="4">
            <text> We cannot conclude anything; it will depend on the other rows</text>
          </choice>
        </choicegroup>
      </multiplechoiceresponse>
    </p>
    <p>
      <solution>
        <font color="blue">Answer: </font>
        <font color="blue">
          <p>
The previous problem gave us an example of a system that is consistent, but has more than one solution. The augmented matrix </p>
          <table id="a0000000020" class="equation" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="7" style="table-layout:auto">
            <tr>
              <td class="equation" style="width:80%;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center;border-style:hidden">[mathjax]\left[ \begin{array}{cc:c} 1&amp; 0&amp; 1 \\ 0&amp; 1&amp; 2\\ 0&amp; 0&amp; 0\\ \end{array} \right][/mathjax]</td>
              <td class="eqnnum" style="width:20%;vertical-align:middle;text-align:left;border-style:hidden"/>
            </tr>
          </table>
          <p>
 is an example of a consistent system with a unique solution. </p>
          <p>
We may also have an inconsistent system such as </p>
          <table id="a0000000021" class="equation" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="7" style="table-layout:auto">
            <tr>
              <td class="equation" style="width:80%;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center;border-style:hidden">[mathjax]\left[ \begin{array}{cc:c} 1&amp; 0&amp; 1 \\ 0&amp; 0&amp; 1\\ 0&amp; 0&amp; 0\\ \end{array} \right][/mathjax]</td>
              <td class="eqnnum" style="width:20%;vertical-align:middle;text-align:left;border-style:hidden"/>
            </tr>
          </table>
        </font>
      </solution>
    </p>
  </text>
</problem>
